[
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfEmyNCqIsQ1PpfBjCkXJUSB/shulman.jpg\">I'm a bit confused by this old comment of <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span>'s on the n-Cafe:</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfEmyNCqIsQ1PpfBjCkXJUSB/shulman.jpg\" title=\"I'm a bit confused by this old comment of \"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfEmyNCqIsQ1PpfBjCkXJUSB/shulman.jpg\"></a></div>",
        "id": 245634264,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048305
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Let me just discuss the case of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, using classical logic.</p>",
        "id": 245634271,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048329
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Set}^{\\rm op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.737622em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.737622em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362300000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is equivalent to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{CABA}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">CABA</span></span></span></span></span>, the category of complete atomic boolean algebras.</p>",
        "id": 245634331,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048381
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111111111111111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333333333333333em\"/><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\colon \\mathrm{Set}^{\\rm op} \\to \\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.737622em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111111111111111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333333333333333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.737622em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362300000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> is monadic, this implies <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{CABA}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">CABA</span></span></span></span></span> is monadic over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 245634347,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would like to understand this monad rather explicitly.   Mike says the adjoint of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is just \" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> itself\", or a bit more cautiously it's the functor I'll call </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> Q : \\mathrm{Set} \\to \\mathrm{Set}^{\\rm op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.737622em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.737622em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362300000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> </p>\n<p>which is just another way of thinking about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 245634468,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So the monad is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Q</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PQ : \\mathrm{Set} \\to \\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">PQ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 245634523,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048753
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I want to keep on talking until I get to my actual questions.</p>",
        "id": 245634537,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048819
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PQ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">PQ</span></span></span></span> is a bit scary since it's \"without rank\", i.e. it's not a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>-ary monad for any cardinal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>.  So we have to be a bit careful with it.</p>",
        "id": 245634583,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626048877
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I have a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>-ary monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> we can associate to it  a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>-ary algebraic theory whose algebras are the same as algebras of the monad.   For any cardinal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha \\lt \\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span> we can define the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>- ary operations of this algebraic theory to be the set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T(\\alpha)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> (which makes sense since <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> is a set).</p>",
        "id": 245634659,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I will try doing this for the monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PQ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">PQ</span></span></span></span>, with a bit of trepidation since it's a monad without rank.</p>",
        "id": 245634702,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049109
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If this works, the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>-ary operations for complete atomic boolean algebras form the set </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></msup></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(Q(\\alpha)) = 2^{2^\\alpha} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.87998em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.87998em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7385428571428572em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.07142857142857144em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 245634719,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049169
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Now, this seems to make sense.  For example, when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> is finite, we are used to the fact that boolean algebras have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></msup></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2^{2^\\alpha}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.87998em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.87998em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7385428571428572em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.07142857142857144em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> different <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> -ary operations.  We usually draw these as truth tables!     Here are the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2^{2^2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9869199999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9869199999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913142857142857em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.07142857142857144em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> different binary operations for boolean algebras:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/AeZB180cqkQU4IDkabNeqWXZ/Capture22.png\">binary operations for boolean algebras</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/AeZB180cqkQU4IDkabNeqWXZ/Capture22.png\" title=\"binary operations for boolean algebras\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/AeZB180cqkQU4IDkabNeqWXZ/Capture22.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 245634806,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049314
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But we are letting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> be <em>any</em> cardinal.  </p>\n<p>So my question is: are complete atomic boolean algebras precisely the algebras of some algebraic theory without rank, whose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>-ary operations form the set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></msup></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(Q(\\alpha)) = 2^{2^\\alpha} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.87998em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.87998em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7385428571428572em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.07142857142857144em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 245635032,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049655
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And if so, what I want to understand is this: why are the algebras of this monad precisely the complete <em>atomic</em> boolean algebras?</p>",
        "id": 245635084,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049698
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's easy for me to imagine that any complete boolean algebra will be an algebra of some algebraic theory whose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>-ary operations form the set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(Q(\\alpha))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 245635113,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049785
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But this may be false.   </p>\n<p>How does the <em>atomicity</em> of a complete atomic boolean algebra get captured by the operations in an algebraic theory, and the laws obeyed by these operations?</p>",
        "id": 245635251,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626049976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For some related subtleties see Section 6 here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/complete+Boolean+algebra#algebraicity\">Complete Boolean algebra</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 245635260,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626050033
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This section says complete boolean algebras are algebras of some algebraic theory, but that there is no corresponding monad: there is no free complete boolean algebra on an infinite set.</p>",
        "id": 245635325,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626050134
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's about complete boolean algebras... but my question is about complete atomic boolean algebras.</p>",
        "id": 245635370,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626050182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How does atomicity change things?</p>",
        "id": 245635382,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626050255
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This probably won’t answer your question but there is a syntactic presentation of this ‘double power set theory’ in Ernest Manes’ book ‘Algebraic Theories’ (which is actually a book about monads)</p>",
        "id": 245635444,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1626050344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And a more detailed analysis of this monad and it’s algebras.</p>",
        "id": 245635504,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1626050418
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Martin Brandenburg remarks here (Example 6.8) that atomicity = complete distributivity, which is an algebraic condition.<br>\n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.11115.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.11115.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 245635702,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1626050790
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the paper also answers your implicit question about axiomatisability of monads without rank.</p>",
        "id": 245635774,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1626050967
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, Zhen!   If atomiticity is equivalent to complete distributivity, that answers my question.  I hadn't suspected that.</p>\n<p>And thanks, Fawzi: I'd really like to see a syntactic presentation of this theory.   I haven't looked at Manes' book.</p>",
        "id": 245638387,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626055650
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Brandenburg writes:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Now Definition 5.16 allows us to define CABAs internal to any complete category C. This might be surprising, since a priori <em>atomic</em> is not an algebraic condition, but actually it is equivalent to <em>completely distributive</em> by [31, Proposition VII.1.16], and this is an algebraic condition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Here [31] is</p>\n<ul>\n<li>P. T. Johnstone, <em>Stone Spaces</em>, Cambridge Studies in Advanced Mathematics Vol. 3, Cambridge University Press, 1982.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>so that's where I need to look!</p>",
        "id": 245639414,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626057479
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Brandenburg also writes:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Manes explains in [47, Example 3.46] directly why <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>P</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\tilde{P}(P(X))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1701899999999998em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9201899999999998em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.6023300000000003em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.16666em;\"><span class=\"mord\">~</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> is the free CABA on a set X.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 245639476,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626057545
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here his <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>P</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\tilde{P}(P(X))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1701899999999998em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9201899999999998em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.6023300000000003em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.16666em;\"><span class=\"mord\">~</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> is my <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(Q(X))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span>, and [47] is</p>\n<ul>\n<li>E. Manes, Monads of sets, Handbook of algebra. Vol. 3. North-Holland, 2003, 67-153</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 245639678,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1626057880
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think I've ever worked out explicitly how this happens.  But it should also be possible to just <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>β</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\beta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span></span></span></span>-reduce the proof of monadicity of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> and then apply the known equivalence between powersets and CABAs.</p>",
        "id": 245641600,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1626061000
    }
]